<TEI xmlns="http://www.tei-c.org/ns/1.0" xmlns:frus="http://history.state.gov/frus/ns/1.0"><text><body><div frus:doc-dateTime-max="1919-12-27T20:00:00-05:00" frus:doc-dateTime-min="1919-12-27T20:00:00-05:00" n="524" subtype="historical-document" type="document" xml:id="d524">
                            <note rend="inline" type="source">893.51/2598a: Telegram</note>
                            <head><hi rend="italic">The <gloss type="from">Acting Secretary of
                                        State</gloss> to the Ambassador in France</hi> (<persName type="to"><hi rend="italic">Wallace</hi></persName>)</head>
                            <opener><seg rendition="#center">[Extract]</seg></opener>
                            <opener><dateline rendition="#right"><placeName><hi rend="smallcaps">Washington</hi></placeName>, <date calendar="gregorian" when="1919-12-27T20:00:00-05:00"><hi rend="italic">December
                                            27, 1919, 8 p.m.</hi></date></dateline></opener>
                            <p>9441. French apparently unwilling to proceed with $25,000,000 four
                                power loan to China unless disbandment of certain troops appears as
                                condition precedent. England has agreed with us and we are just
                                advised Japan agrees with England. Please cable why French
                                Government takes this attitude. …</p>
                            <closer><signed><hi rend="smallcaps">Polk</hi></signed></closer>
                        </div>
                        </body></text></TEI>